00:06:54.480 --> 00:07:01.280
Now, contrast is interesting because
contrast is taking the left half,

00:07:01.470 --> 00:07:05.960
the parts below the middle and
the parts above the middle,

00:07:05.960 --> 00:07:09.450
and bending the middles of
those portions either toward the

00:07:09.450 --> 00:07:11.440
center or away from the center.

00:07:11.560 --> 00:07:14.540
Anybody who's familiar with doing
this in something like Photoshop,

00:07:14.620 --> 00:07:16.960
you'd use an S-curve and
you'd bend the S-curve.

00:07:17.110 --> 00:07:21.490
And what that has the effect of
doing is moving the lower and upper

00:07:21.490 --> 00:07:27.040
brightnesses of the image either toward
the center or away from the center.

00:07:27.160 --> 00:07:32.430
But what we found was that all of these
things laid out along a single line.

00:07:32.560 --> 00:07:36.400
We had dark adjustments on the left,
bright on the right,

00:07:36.530 --> 00:07:39.740
brightness in the middle,
and then contrast in the

00:07:39.740 --> 00:07:41.750
two halves between that.

00:07:41.890 --> 00:07:44.460
So we could lay these
out on a single line.

00:07:44.570 --> 00:07:51.100
So what the first kind of design revision
was to take and still have the histogram

00:07:51.100 --> 00:07:53.800
over on the side and laid this out.

00:07:53.870 --> 00:07:56.960
And we said, OK,
you can touch this upper part

00:07:56.960 --> 00:08:01.200
of the histogram and pull it
down to do highlight recovery

00:08:01.200 --> 00:08:03.440
and up to do white point adjust.

00:08:03.570 --> 00:08:08.920
You can do shadows and black point by
touching the bottom of the histogram.

00:08:09.160 --> 00:08:11.710
You can touch the center of the
histogram and bend it up and

00:08:11.710 --> 00:08:14.040
down to do a brightness adjust.

00:08:14.110 --> 00:08:16.800
And you can touch either of these
two areas and do a contrast adjust.

00:08:16.800 --> 00:08:23.000
Now, that reduces the number of
points where you're touching.

00:08:23.090 --> 00:08:26.010
But it also had the interesting
side effect that now we have no

00:08:26.010 --> 00:08:28.640
affordances on this histogram.

00:08:28.740 --> 00:08:31.760
And people would look at it and say, oh,
that's a nice histogram.

00:08:31.990 --> 00:08:34.100
And oh, no,
you can adjust the brightness here.

00:08:34.240 --> 00:08:35.810
How do they know that?

00:08:35.900 --> 00:08:37.890
This went too far in the other direction.

00:08:38.020 --> 00:08:42.230
We actually didn't have anything
that was obvious to adjust.

00:08:42.580 --> 00:08:47.130
Now,
the other thing here is that we have--

00:08:47.260 --> 00:08:49.780
this is a photo editing application.

00:08:49.880 --> 00:08:55.940
And you'll notice the photo is
occupying maybe 70% of the screen.

00:08:56.030 --> 00:08:57.280
And this is a really important point.

00:08:57.280 --> 00:09:00.200
With any kind of application,
whatever the main focus

00:09:00.200 --> 00:09:03.890
of the application is,
you want that to occupy as

00:09:03.890 --> 00:09:06.080
much of the screen as possible.

00:09:06.080 --> 00:09:09.950
It's one thing on a desktop application
when you've got expecting someone to

00:09:09.950 --> 00:09:14.900
be working on a 20 or a 23 or 27-inch
monitor where there's plenty of room.

00:09:14.920 --> 00:09:20.050
Well, on mobile devices,
especially phones, but even the iPad,

00:09:20.050 --> 00:09:23.380
there's not as much screen real
estate as there is on the desktop.

00:09:23.470 --> 00:09:25.660
So you want to use that very carefully.

00:09:25.660 --> 00:09:30.590
And you want to give up screen real
estate that you could put towards

00:09:30.590 --> 00:09:33.460
the primary focus of the application.

00:09:33.500 --> 00:09:37.690
You want to give that up very cautiously,
only as needed.

00:09:37.850 --> 00:09:41.690
So we looked at this and said, OK,
we really-- what would be nice here is

00:09:41.690 --> 00:09:47.360
if we took this space over on the side
and didn't use that for the histogram.

00:09:47.360 --> 00:09:52.700
If we took the histogram and instead
put it down along the bottom.

00:09:52.710 --> 00:09:54.480
And you can see we have
the same histogram,

00:09:54.590 --> 00:09:57.320
kind of the same areas to touch on there.

00:09:57.650 --> 00:10:01.230
But what the nice thing is about
this is it gives us a nice,

00:10:01.230 --> 00:10:02.520
big, giant image.

00:10:02.570 --> 00:10:06.580
And it makes it so you can
see your image a lot better.

00:10:07.020 --> 00:10:09.990
Now we had this control
down here at the bottom,

00:10:09.990 --> 00:10:13.900
and like the other ones that I've shown,
we had a histogram in it.

00:10:14.080 --> 00:10:17.900
And so we kind of stepped back and said,
"Okay, why do we need this histogram?"

00:10:17.900 --> 00:10:21.020
A lot of photography applications
have a histogram in them,

00:10:21.020 --> 00:10:22.900
and, you know, why exactly do we need it?

00:10:22.900 --> 00:10:24.900
What's the important parts here?

00:10:24.900 --> 00:10:27.880
Well, a histogram shows you some
interesting things about an image.

00:10:27.950 --> 00:10:30.850
Like I said before,
this tells me that this image

00:10:31.180 --> 00:10:33.900
has some brighter blue parts,
and the red and green parts

00:10:33.900 --> 00:10:37.530
are not quite as bright,
which is interesting,

00:10:37.820 --> 00:10:42.890
but it doesn't really help you in
terms of adjusting or fixing the image.

00:10:43.090 --> 00:10:48.590
The part that's actually interesting for
fixing or adjusting the image is actually

00:10:48.940 --> 00:10:53.900
just the end points of the histogram,
where those end points are.

00:10:54.100 --> 00:10:57.830
What that tells you, on the left side,
that tells me how close to black

00:10:57.830 --> 00:10:59.900
are the darkest parts of my image.

00:10:59.900 --> 00:11:02.780
And on the right,
how close to pure white are the

00:11:03.020 --> 00:11:04.890
brightest parts of my image.

00:11:04.900 --> 00:11:10.700
This is actually what's useful in
terms of image editing on an image.

00:11:10.900 --> 00:11:14.190
So given that, we said, "Well,
we don't really need to

00:11:14.190 --> 00:11:15.900
show the histogram at all.

00:11:15.900 --> 00:11:20.900
We just need to show the ends
of what would be the histogram."

00:11:20.900 --> 00:11:25.600
So taking all that together,
what we did is we combined

00:11:25.680 --> 00:11:28.900
everything into a single control.

00:11:29.010 --> 00:11:33.900
We've got a single control that
has marks on it for 0% and 100%.

00:11:33.900 --> 00:11:36.900
On the left side -- or sorry,
in the center,

00:11:36.960 --> 00:11:38.900
we put a brightness control.

00:11:38.900 --> 00:11:41.900
On the left side,
we put a single control.

00:11:42.060 --> 00:11:46.750
When I drag this control to the left,
I'm doing black level adjust.

00:11:47.090 --> 00:11:49.760
When I drag to the right,
I'm doing shadow recovery.

00:11:49.970 --> 00:11:57.890
And the initial position of that knob is
where the left end of the histogram is.

00:11:58.010 --> 00:11:59.900
We do the same thing on the right side.

00:12:00.040 --> 00:12:02.900
So highlight recovery is dragging left.

00:12:02.900 --> 00:12:04.890
White level adjust is dragging right.

00:12:05.150 --> 00:12:11.850
And the initial position of that knob
shows me the right end of the histogram.

00:12:11.900 --> 00:12:15.100
So we've been able to
combine those six -- well,

00:12:15.190 --> 00:12:18.620
brightness in the center,
but the six controls into the two

00:12:18.620 --> 00:12:24.900
on the two ends and put them in
a much more usable configuration.

00:12:25.040 --> 00:12:28.890
Then we also took the contrast
knobs and put those in kind of

00:12:28.890 --> 00:12:31.900
the corresponding areas to where
they correspond to in the image.

00:12:31.900 --> 00:12:35.540
And then we also -- the one thing
that I talked about initially that

00:12:35.550 --> 00:12:37.840
we haven't shown so far is clipping.

00:12:37.900 --> 00:12:40.450
How do you show when an
adjustment the user is going

00:12:40.450 --> 00:12:44.260
to make is clipping the image,
is cutting off some of the darks

00:12:44.260 --> 00:12:45.900
or cutting off some of the lights?

00:12:45.900 --> 00:12:50.900
We actually do that by -- when the
knob is dragged into that range,

00:12:51.190 --> 00:12:55.900
since the knob represents the edge of
the brights and darks of the image,

00:12:55.980 --> 00:13:00.900
when we drag into the end zones,
they glow red as you drag into them.

00:13:00.900 --> 00:13:03.620
We do that all on a single control.

00:13:03.900 --> 00:13:09.370
And so what we're able to do is put
this all down into the lower toolbar

00:13:09.990 --> 00:13:14.900
and have a single control that gives
all these different operations.

00:13:14.990 --> 00:13:19.340
Let me just give you a quick demo of how
that actually works in the application.

00:13:19.970 --> 00:13:23.680
We'll switch to an image here.

00:13:23.790 --> 00:13:28.060
So we have this image,
and if I bring up my exposure control,

00:13:28.150 --> 00:13:34.020
you can see that the ends of
the control are not all the

00:13:34.020 --> 00:13:38.890
way at the 0 and 100% marks,
because this image does not--

00:13:38.900 --> 00:13:40.600
actually has a reduced range.

00:13:40.600 --> 00:13:44.170
The blackest parts of the
image are still kind of gray,

00:13:44.280 --> 00:13:47.680
and the brightest part of
the image is not pure white.

00:13:47.800 --> 00:13:49.500
But I can grab these controls.

00:13:49.500 --> 00:13:51.870
If I grab the control here
and move it up or down,

00:13:51.940 --> 00:13:54.500
when I move it down,
I'm adjusting the black level down.

00:13:54.610 --> 00:13:59.100
As I move into the end area,
you'll see that it starts to glow red,

00:13:59.130 --> 00:14:02.000
because it's not necessarily
incorrect for someone to

00:14:02.060 --> 00:14:03.750
clip off some of the blacks.

00:14:03.860 --> 00:14:04.940
They may want to do that.

00:14:05.120 --> 00:14:08.170
You just want to warn them that
this is an area where they have

00:14:08.170 --> 00:14:09.900
to make a creative decision.

00:14:10.010 --> 00:14:15.000
And when I grab the right side,
I can bring that up to white.

00:14:15.510 --> 00:14:18.490
And so you can actually see
the difference between the

00:14:18.490 --> 00:14:22.600
original and the changed one
as I've made those adjustments.

00:14:22.700 --> 00:14:26.550
Now,
let me come down to another image here,

00:14:26.550 --> 00:14:28.100
which is really dark.

00:14:28.200 --> 00:14:31.800
And you'll notice on this image,
the darks go all the way to black,

00:14:31.920 --> 00:14:34.410
all the way to the left,
so the knob starts out all

00:14:34.410 --> 00:14:36.060
the way there at the left.

00:14:36.170 --> 00:14:40.630
And the brightest parts of the image,
the lights and such,

00:14:40.630 --> 00:14:45.570
actually go all the way to 100%. So here,
if I grab the left-hand knob

00:14:45.820 --> 00:14:48.930
and I drag it to the right,
what I'm actually doing

00:14:49.210 --> 00:14:50.800
is shadow correction.

00:14:50.850 --> 00:14:55.070
I'm not just bringing up the black level,
I'm doing a shadow correction.

00:14:55.280 --> 00:14:58.330
The nice thing here is that
from the user's perspective,

00:14:58.330 --> 00:15:00.980
they just get to think about
the dark parts of the image

00:15:00.990 --> 00:15:02.760
should be darker or lighter.

00:15:03.090 --> 00:15:06.870
And we do the right math underneath
the covers to achieve that.

00:15:06.990 --> 00:15:09.300
We don't force the user
to make the distinction,

00:15:09.370 --> 00:15:11.600
oh, in this case,
I need to use this slider.

00:15:11.600 --> 00:15:14.370
In this other case,
I need to use this other slider.

00:15:14.480 --> 00:15:19.020
We merge that all together into a
single control and make it really

00:15:19.020 --> 00:15:20.930
easy for the user to do that.

00:15:21.030 --> 00:15:24.010
So next thing I want to
talk about is brushes,

00:15:24.040 --> 00:15:27.230
because we've got some nice
brushes in the application.

00:15:27.380 --> 00:15:31.440
So initial sort of stab at
this was something that would

00:15:31.440 --> 00:15:36.080
look more like what a sort of
desktop-like experience might be.

00:15:36.190 --> 00:15:38.500
We started out with, well,
you can add these different bricks

00:15:38.550 --> 00:15:39.860
for the different operations.

00:15:39.880 --> 00:15:43.670
You can add a brick
for lighten or darken.

00:15:43.870 --> 00:15:46.810
But that makes the user have
to make those decisions as they

00:15:46.810 --> 00:15:50.710
go along and then actually add
those bricks in as they work.

00:15:50.840 --> 00:15:53.400
And it complicates the UI quite a bit.

00:15:53.400 --> 00:15:58.990
So second stab was to just take the
brushes that the user would most likely

00:15:58.990 --> 00:16:03.820
want to use and just make those available
all the time so that they can just touch

00:16:03.820 --> 00:16:06.360
on one of the brushes and start using it.

00:16:06.560 --> 00:16:11.500
Well, that's an improvement,
but once again,

00:16:11.500 --> 00:16:16.760
we have the issue here that the
image is not as big as it could be.

00:16:16.760 --> 00:16:20.040
So if we take those controls and
move them down along the bottom,

00:16:20.110 --> 00:16:21.310
that's better.

00:16:21.480 --> 00:16:26.450
But now we're in a situation where
we have these icons down here,

00:16:26.460 --> 00:16:30.950
and we're trying to represent in these
icons that these are painting operations,

00:16:30.950 --> 00:16:33.820
and we're trying to make
up icons for things like

00:16:33.820 --> 00:16:36.990
lighten and darken and repair,
and it can be hard to

00:16:37.220 --> 00:16:39.360
get those to stand out.

00:16:39.480 --> 00:16:45.680
So the thing that we came to was,
as you may have seen,

00:16:45.770 --> 00:16:48.460
we've got these nice brushes that pop up.

00:16:48.460 --> 00:16:52.540
And these are very
familiar looking to a user.

00:16:52.540 --> 00:16:56.290
One of the nice things here is that
we decided that it was okay while

00:16:56.300 --> 00:17:00.590
you're selecting a brush to break
the boundary of that lower toolbar.

00:17:00.670 --> 00:17:01.800
As the brushes come up,
you can see that the lower toolbar

00:17:01.800 --> 00:17:01.800
is the boundary of the lower toolbar.

00:17:01.800 --> 00:17:01.800
And you can see that the lower toolbar
is the boundary of the lower toolbar.

00:17:01.800 --> 00:17:01.800
And you can see that the lower toolbar
is the boundary of the lower toolbar.

00:17:01.800 --> 00:17:01.850
And you can see that the lower toolbar
is the boundary of the lower toolbar.

00:17:01.850 --> 00:17:02.150
And you can see that the lower toolbar
is the boundary of the lower toolbar.

00:17:02.240 --> 00:17:04.430
The brushes go up above the toolbar.

00:17:04.500 --> 00:17:08.520
We dim out the rest of the
interface to make the brushes pop.

00:17:08.520 --> 00:17:11.600
The user makes a selection,
and then the brushes

00:17:11.800 --> 00:17:15.560
tuck down into the UI,
down into the bottom bar there.

00:17:15.560 --> 00:17:19.500
Another thing that we did with
the brushes was multi-touch is

00:17:19.740 --> 00:17:21.660
really powerful for painting.

00:17:21.660 --> 00:17:26.330
It feels really good to use your
finger as you're painting on the image.

00:17:26.330 --> 00:17:31.580
But in a lot of painting applications,
there are a bunch of controls for things

00:17:31.600 --> 00:17:35.170
like like the opacity of the brush,
the size of the brush,

00:17:35.230 --> 00:17:39.380
the softness of the brush,
and that just complicates the experience.

00:17:39.380 --> 00:17:42.060
So we step back and said,
how can we make that easier?

00:17:42.070 --> 00:17:44.780
Well, first off,
if we say that the size of

00:17:44.780 --> 00:17:49.160
your finger is constant,
then we can just say when you zoom in,

00:17:49.410 --> 00:17:52.420
then your finger stays
the same on screen,

00:17:52.510 --> 00:17:57.420
but now occupies a smaller
portion of the zoomed image.

00:17:57.420 --> 00:18:01.520
So brush size is simply
done by zooming in.

00:18:01.600 --> 00:18:04.260
And in fact,
one of the lesser known features

00:18:04.420 --> 00:18:08.550
of the app is that if you pinch
together to zoom all the way back

00:18:08.580 --> 00:18:11.800
out to seeing the entire image,
if you pinch beyond that where

00:18:12.110 --> 00:18:15.350
the image kind of shrinks down and
hold it there for half a second,

00:18:15.350 --> 00:18:18.440
the image will actually
snap a little bit smaller.

00:18:18.440 --> 00:18:21.080
So it actually lets you make the image
even smaller so you can make your

00:18:21.080 --> 00:18:24.280
finger work even on an even larger area.

00:18:24.280 --> 00:18:26.850
