So that was our way of allowing the brush

00:18:26.860 --> 00:18:30.180
to have a lot of different range to it.

00:18:30.180 --> 00:18:34.180
The other thing we did is we set the
brushes up to operate fairly lightly,

00:18:34.400 --> 00:18:35.910
and they overlap each other.

00:18:35.910 --> 00:18:38.590
The brushes keep,
as you rub your finger back and forth,

00:18:38.590 --> 00:18:40.500
they keep adding to it.

00:18:40.500 --> 00:18:43.530
So instead of having a lot
of paint applications where

00:18:43.530 --> 00:18:46.560
the brush is very strong,
you make a swipe and then you end up

00:18:46.560 --> 00:18:49.840
having to erase almost immediately
and then turn the brush down.

00:18:49.920 --> 00:18:51.710
We set them to work very softly.

00:18:51.710 --> 00:18:55.000
So the idea is that when you're
going to change somebody's face,

00:18:55.100 --> 00:18:56.370
you just rub over it a few times.

00:18:56.490 --> 00:18:58.300
It feels very natural.

00:18:58.300 --> 00:19:01.000
You rarely have to go back and erase.

00:19:01.000 --> 00:19:04.630
The other thing you run into
with a painting application is

00:19:04.820 --> 00:19:07.980
that if you're trying to get
something right along an edge,

00:19:07.980 --> 00:19:11.530
the problem you run into is that your
finger is over the top of the edge that

00:19:11.810 --> 00:19:13.780
you're trying to get right up against.

00:19:13.790 --> 00:19:16.020
And we looked at different
solutions to that,

00:19:16.020 --> 00:19:20.030
like putting a circle around where your
finger was so you could kind of see it.

00:19:20.110 --> 00:19:23.320
But that all felt like we were just
sort of band-aiding the problem.

00:19:23.390 --> 00:19:25.110
Subtitles by the Amara.org community
And what we ended up solving

00:19:25.110 --> 00:19:29.000
was down in the lower right we
have this detect edges button.

00:19:29.100 --> 00:19:32.120
We wrote some code that
actually when you turn that on,

00:19:32.370 --> 00:19:35.430
wherever you touch,
we pick up the color and lightness

00:19:35.480 --> 00:19:39.440
of the spot you touch on and we
restrict painting from that point,

00:19:39.440 --> 00:19:42.800
for that stroke,
to only affect things within a certain

00:19:42.800 --> 00:19:45.540
range of that lightness and color.

00:19:45.540 --> 00:19:47.360
So what it means is you can
touch down on something.

00:19:47.380 --> 00:19:49.740
It's sort of like automatic
color within the lines.

00:19:49.870 --> 00:19:52.380
And you can just run your
finger back and forth very

00:19:52.380 --> 00:19:53.960
quickly and it stays just fine.

00:19:53.960 --> 00:19:55.360
And then you can adjust on that color.

00:19:55.360 --> 00:19:59.260
So we let the application figure
out where the edges are instead

00:19:59.260 --> 00:20:01.480
of forcing the user to do that.

00:20:01.590 --> 00:20:06.860
So that was some of the solutions
we used for the paint function.

00:20:06.860 --> 00:20:10.010
So next up I'm going to turn it
over to Sam to talk about color.

00:20:14.020 --> 00:20:15.120
Good morning.

00:20:15.460 --> 00:20:19.340
Thanks for waking up early with
us to talk about iPhoto for iOS.

00:20:19.480 --> 00:20:23.140
Color is a really important part
about manipulating an image,

00:20:23.200 --> 00:20:25.160
and there's a lot of ways to do it.

00:20:25.360 --> 00:20:28.690
And some of the lessons that
we learned when we created this

00:20:28.720 --> 00:20:32.270
feature for iPhoto for iOS,
I think some of these lessons might be

00:20:32.270 --> 00:20:35.840
able to apply to some of the amazing
apps that you guys are working on.

00:20:35.920 --> 00:20:38.360
So I'd like to share
some of that with you.

00:20:38.440 --> 00:20:40.360
Like I said,
there's a ton of ways to adjust color.

00:20:40.360 --> 00:20:44.000
If you use Photoshop or any sort of
professional image editing application,

00:20:44.090 --> 00:20:46.600
you know there are loads
and loads of tools.

00:20:46.670 --> 00:20:49.440
And presenting our user,
especially the iPhoto user,

00:20:49.510 --> 00:20:53.360
with a ton of tools to adjust color,
that was the wrong approach.

00:20:53.420 --> 00:20:56.370
Our users, we knew they could get quickly
sort of overwhelmed with

00:20:56.460 --> 00:20:58.050
a whole bunch of controls.

00:20:58.170 --> 00:21:02.340
So our first challenge with
color was to step back and say,

00:21:02.340 --> 00:21:05.060
"Okay, well,
what are the most common things,

00:21:05.150 --> 00:21:10.160
what are the most common color needs
that our users have?" And we narrowed it

00:21:10.260 --> 00:21:13.230
down to more or less these four controls.

00:21:13.240 --> 00:21:18.040
The first one is overall color,
saturation, how much color do we want?

00:21:18.040 --> 00:21:21.440
And then we sort of found three
other areas that were really common.

00:21:21.440 --> 00:21:24.360
A lot of people would say, "Well,
I want the blue sky of my image

00:21:24.360 --> 00:21:27.540
to be a little bit different." Or,
"You know, the skin tone of this image

00:21:27.540 --> 00:21:28.540
just looks a little off.

00:21:28.540 --> 00:21:30.380
I want to be able to
adjust that." And then,

00:21:30.380 --> 00:21:32.240
of course, also the greenery.

00:21:32.240 --> 00:21:35.230
So that was the first step was to say,
"Yes, we have a ton of controls,

00:21:35.240 --> 00:21:36.770
but do we really need them all?

00:21:36.830 --> 00:21:37.800
A ton of functions?

00:21:37.800 --> 00:21:42.960
No, let's find the functions that work
for the 80% case." This is something

00:21:43.650 --> 00:21:45.280
that we say a lot to ourselves.

00:21:45.280 --> 00:21:46.780
What's the 80% case?

00:21:46.780 --> 00:21:47.920
Let's solve for that.

00:21:47.920 --> 00:21:52.200
Let's not try and figure out one thing
that's going to work for everyone.

00:21:52.380 --> 00:21:54.800
So this was our first stab at color.

00:21:54.860 --> 00:21:56.530
And it's OK.

00:21:56.640 --> 00:21:58.680
The controls are few,
but the controls are actually

00:21:58.680 --> 00:21:59.940
a little bit technical.

00:21:59.940 --> 00:22:02.000
As you can see,
for each one of these areas,

00:22:02.020 --> 00:22:06.040
you sort of had to move on two axes
to sort of adjust the luminance and

00:22:06.040 --> 00:22:09.210
then the amount of that color space.

00:22:09.320 --> 00:22:12.060
That was cool, but that was a little bit
complicated for a user.

00:22:12.060 --> 00:22:16.840
So our next step was to say, OK,
let's take those four good ideas

00:22:16.880 --> 00:22:18.450
and let's simplify those controls.

00:22:18.460 --> 00:22:20.620
Let's do some smart
math behind the scenes.

00:22:20.810 --> 00:22:23.360
I'm a designer,
so I let the geniuses do the math,

00:22:23.420 --> 00:22:25.200
and I just designed the controls.

00:22:25.300 --> 00:22:29.230
And they figured out a way to say, OK,
well, less saturation means this,

00:22:29.230 --> 00:22:30.700
more saturation means that.

00:22:30.790 --> 00:22:33.450
So we got it into sort of one,
you could say,

00:22:33.450 --> 00:22:35.760
axis for each one of these controls.

00:22:35.980 --> 00:22:38.530
So this is significantly simpler, right?

00:22:38.780 --> 00:22:41.140
If I want more color,
I simply drag left or right on

00:22:41.140 --> 00:22:44.820
the saturation control over there,
and I can adjust the color.

00:22:44.870 --> 00:22:46.320
So now we're starting to get somewhere.

00:22:46.320 --> 00:22:50.670
Now we have sort of an easier experience,
which is what our customers want.

00:22:50.760 --> 00:22:56.810
But as Randy said before,
we still have a problem with this design.

00:22:56.920 --> 00:22:59.320
This is a photo editing app.

00:22:59.340 --> 00:23:02.220
The user started this app because
they want to play with their photos.

00:23:02.250 --> 00:23:04.960
But we're giving them all of this Chrome,
all of this UI,

00:23:04.970 --> 00:23:07.280
that's sort of getting in the way.

00:23:07.290 --> 00:23:09.140
I really want to drive this home.

00:23:09.160 --> 00:23:10.800
You guys are making great apps.

00:23:10.940 --> 00:23:15.940
And the main purpose of your app
should always dominate the screen.

00:23:15.960 --> 00:23:18.970
Your users didn't buy
your app for the Chrome,

00:23:19.100 --> 00:23:20.780
for the controls that you created.

00:23:20.790 --> 00:23:25.380
They bought it to be able to do what
they want to do with their content.

00:23:25.380 --> 00:23:26.380
This was really central.

00:23:26.440 --> 00:23:29.890
So as soon as we sort of realized that,
we got that image much

00:23:29.890 --> 00:23:31.130
bigger on the screen.

00:23:31.240 --> 00:23:32.620
Gosh, this felt so much better.

00:23:32.620 --> 00:23:35.100
We put those same controls
down along the bottom.

00:23:35.140 --> 00:23:36.160
Now we're really talking.

00:23:36.160 --> 00:23:39.510
I've got this big image, simple controls.

00:23:39.660 --> 00:23:41.680
Here we are.

00:23:41.700 --> 00:23:43.040
But--

00:23:43.750 --> 00:23:49.720
The benefit of continuing to push
our UI brought us to a place that

00:23:49.720 --> 00:23:52.190
we wouldn't have seen otherwise.

00:23:52.330 --> 00:23:55.340
Something that we
constantly say is simplify,

00:23:55.410 --> 00:23:57.660
refine, repeat.

00:23:57.780 --> 00:23:59.890
Simplify, refine, repeat.

00:23:59.980 --> 00:24:00.890
That's really important.

00:24:00.900 --> 00:24:03.840
If we hadn't have kept doing that,
we wouldn't have gotten to this.

00:24:04.150 --> 00:24:05.100
Because we realized something.

00:24:05.100 --> 00:24:08.820
As soon as we had that big image--
I was using the app one day.

00:24:08.880 --> 00:24:10.340
And they said, you know,
I just want to edit

00:24:10.520 --> 00:24:13.200
this part of my image.

00:24:13.440 --> 00:24:15.940
And I was pointing to that
part of the image and I said,

00:24:15.960 --> 00:24:18.140
"Wait a minute,
we have a touchscreen interface here.

00:24:18.140 --> 00:24:20.060
We have an amazing piece of hardware.

00:24:20.120 --> 00:24:21.460
We've got a nice big photo.

00:24:21.710 --> 00:24:26.060
What if I could just point to the
thing that I want to edit and I could

00:24:26.060 --> 00:24:28.780
edit it right on top of the image?"

00:24:29.410 --> 00:24:31.540
If we had a smaller image,
that wouldn't be realistic.

00:24:31.540 --> 00:24:34.030
If we had complicated controls,
no one would ever try to do that.

00:24:34.340 --> 00:24:38.940
But now, you just simply tap on
a part of the image,

00:24:39.090 --> 00:24:41.420
drag, and you get to adjust the image.

00:24:41.460 --> 00:24:42.200
It's really simple.

00:24:42.200 --> 00:24:44.320
And as you do that,
you can see at the bottom there,

00:24:44.510 --> 00:24:48.350
the controls of sort of the
area that you're tapping appear.

00:24:48.370 --> 00:24:52.380
In other words, they show you sort of an
educational aspect of the UI.

00:24:52.380 --> 00:24:56.300
It says, OK, if you drag up and down,
you can adjust the saturation.

00:24:56.400 --> 00:24:59.390
And if you drag left or right,
you can adjust the blue skies.

00:24:59.580 --> 00:25:01.590
And we repeated that, of course,
for each control.

00:25:01.750 --> 00:25:03.810
So if I tapped on some
of those green areas,

00:25:03.910 --> 00:25:06.160
you would get the green control
at the bottom highlighted.

00:25:06.160 --> 00:25:08.760
And then you could just
drag left and right.

00:25:08.890 --> 00:25:11.430
Put some controls on top of your content.

00:25:11.590 --> 00:25:14.410
That's where people want to go.

00:25:14.510 --> 00:25:16.520
That's where you should
put some of your controls.

00:25:16.630 --> 00:25:19.760
And speaking of repeating,
we were able to bring this idea

00:25:20.270 --> 00:25:23.520
back to the exposure controls that
Randy was showing you earlier.

00:25:23.760 --> 00:25:27.920
So you could simply tap on
a dark area of the screen.

00:25:28.050 --> 00:25:29.530
Or a dark area of the image.

00:25:29.550 --> 00:25:32.020
And drag up to adjust your shadows.

00:25:32.040 --> 00:25:36.920
This is where design that's simplified,
refined, repeat, keep doing that,

00:25:36.920 --> 00:25:40.390
can get you to a space where
the UI almost disappears.

00:25:40.650 --> 00:25:44.480
And there's very little space
between the user and the content,

00:25:44.570 --> 00:25:46.240
the function that they want to do.

00:25:46.310 --> 00:25:49.560
So I want to show you how
this color control works.

00:25:49.640 --> 00:25:52.810
So can we get the iPad up?

00:25:56.250 --> 00:25:57.160
Great.

00:25:57.320 --> 00:26:02.790
So let's go over,
let's clear out the controls.

00:26:02.890 --> 00:26:05.910
Let's go to my color controls.

00:26:05.910 --> 00:26:06.750
And here we have an image.

00:26:06.830 --> 00:26:08.990
You can see the controls have
come up on the bottom there.

00:26:09.260 --> 00:26:13.090
And I could drag these down at
the bottom very easily and adjust

00:26:13.090 --> 00:26:15.300
the amount of color in my image.

00:26:15.460 --> 00:26:17.350
But the cool part is I can say,
you know what,

00:26:17.360 --> 00:26:18.870
I want that blue sky to be better.

00:26:19.200 --> 00:26:22.320
So I can just tap on the blue sky,
my control comes up.

00:26:22.640 --> 00:26:25.600
Now there's a little bit of subtlety
that I want you to notice here.

00:26:25.600 --> 00:26:26.970
You can see there's two axes.

00:26:27.050 --> 00:26:29.780
But we didn't want to complicate
things by having both axes

00:26:29.790 --> 00:26:31.000
available all the time.

00:26:31.090 --> 00:26:33.680
So once the user starts
to move in a direction,

00:26:33.900 --> 00:26:38.200
you're going to see the other arrow sort
of disappear and the arrow that I chose

00:26:38.200 --> 00:26:40.100
sort of move with me and then fade away.

00:26:40.100 --> 00:26:42.330
So, for example,
I'm going to drag to the left and

00:26:42.470 --> 00:26:45.940
you're going to see the saturation
arrows sort of fade away as I do that.

00:26:45.940 --> 00:26:49.850
And now I'm adjusting the blue of
that image so I can get a nice,

00:26:49.850 --> 00:26:51.600
deep, beautiful color.

00:26:51.600 --> 00:26:55.590
This is the power of putting the
control right where the user is.

00:26:55.600 --> 00:26:57.600
So I can see that the user expects
it right on top of the photo.

00:26:57.600 --> 00:26:59.600
So let's try it again.

00:26:59.600 --> 00:27:00.590
This time we're going to
do some exposure work.

00:27:00.600 --> 00:27:03.490
Let's see,
where's that good lighthouse photo?

00:27:03.610 --> 00:27:05.510
Let's play with this one.

00:27:05.600 --> 00:27:08.600
In fact,
let's reset the exposure on this one.

00:27:08.600 --> 00:27:11.600
And that bottom area you
can see is a bit dark.

00:27:11.600 --> 00:27:17.020
So as you would expect,
I can simply tap right on that area

00:27:17.020 --> 00:27:19.480
and drag up to fix the shadows.

00:27:19.600 --> 00:27:21.400
It's really simple.

00:27:21.600 --> 00:27:24.600
It's really simple and it almost
feels magical to the user.

00:27:24.600 --> 00:27:25.600
And that's what we want.

00:27:25.600 --> 00:27:28.550
We want an easy to use, fun interface.

00:27:28.920 --> 00:27:30.600
Just tap on your image.

00:27:30.600 --> 00:27:32.600
It's really powerful.

00:27:32.600 --> 00:27:34.600
So that's the color controls.

00:27:39.640 --> 00:27:42.300
So let's talk about effects.

00:27:42.380 --> 00:27:44.000
I love effects.

00:27:44.100 --> 00:27:47.380
I take mediocre photos,
and those photos look awesome

00:27:47.380 --> 00:27:48.560
with some really great effects.

00:27:48.760 --> 00:27:49.760
Let's be honest, we all do that.

00:27:49.870 --> 00:27:52.160
So effects are really important.

00:27:52.300 --> 00:27:54.490
There's a couple of other people
here who take mediocre photos.

00:27:54.570 --> 00:27:55.590
Great.

00:27:55.730 --> 00:27:59.250
So the first thing that we started
with with effects was a bunch of

00:27:59.440 --> 00:28:01.640
really beautiful-looking effects,
right?

00:28:01.760 --> 00:28:04.700
So some really nice vintage looks,
some black and white,

00:28:04.700 --> 00:28:08.170
some really creative sort of
manipulations with the color.

00:28:08.290 --> 00:28:11.620
Really gorgeous, gorgeous effects.

00:28:11.820 --> 00:28:15.700
And we set ourselves up
with three challenges.

00:28:15.840 --> 00:28:18.180
This is something that you guys
should be doing with any piece

00:28:18.230 --> 00:28:19.540
of UI that you're presented with.

00:28:20.080 --> 00:28:22.090
Figure out, all right,
how can I make this great?

00:28:22.210 --> 00:28:23.190
What are the challenges?

00:28:23.200 --> 00:28:27.200
What can I set as the
goal as I create this UI?

00:28:27.500 --> 00:28:31.610
Okay, so the first challenge-- well,
the first challenge was actually,

00:28:31.840 --> 00:28:33.180
you know, pretty simple.

00:28:33.290 --> 00:28:38.000
We wanted to say, okay,
how can we get all of these amazing

00:28:38.000 --> 00:28:40.140
options available to the user?

00:28:40.200 --> 00:28:43.700
So I'm gonna give you guys a quiz.

00:28:43.700 --> 00:28:44.660
And you're all smart.

00:28:44.730 --> 00:28:45.700
You're all very smart.

00:28:45.700 --> 00:28:48.200
I'm willing to bet you're
gonna get this right.

00:28:48.420 --> 00:28:51.700
Let's say I have 24 amazing effects,
all right?

00:28:51.700 --> 00:28:52.690
In fact, here they are.

00:28:52.700 --> 00:28:53.190
There's a grid.

00:28:53.200 --> 00:28:55.830
You can see there's six of them here,
and you can see just the

00:28:55.830 --> 00:28:58.700
bottom of the next seven,
eight, and nine effects.

00:28:58.810 --> 00:28:59.700
Here's my question.

00:28:59.730 --> 00:29:03.980
Which six effects are
gonna be the most popular?

00:29:04.240 --> 00:29:06.100
Yeah, these six.

00:29:06.240 --> 00:29:08.930
Presenting our effects as a grid
wouldn't have helped the user.

00:29:09.200 --> 00:29:12.600
So that was one of our first
sort of big challenges,

00:29:12.600 --> 00:29:16.720
was to figure out how do we get all these
effects to the user in a way that they're

00:29:16.720 --> 00:29:18.450
going to be able to see all of them.

00:29:18.450 --> 00:29:24.650
We couldn't expect that they
would explore around and see,

00:29:24.700 --> 00:29:26.370
oh, okay, well,
I found the 45th effect and I love it.

00:29:26.370 --> 00:29:26.370
We couldn't assume that.

00:29:26.590 --> 00:29:29.620
The next one, and actually,
this was the hardest one,

00:29:29.620 --> 00:29:32.950
and I really encourage you to do
this as you're creating your apps and

00:29:32.950 --> 00:29:37.740
creating a piece of UI for something,
for a function that might be complicated.

00:29:37.850 --> 00:29:39.440
And this one I can blame on Randy,
actually.

00:29:39.440 --> 00:29:41.740
Randy said, "Okay, Sam,
you can design this UI,

00:29:41.740 --> 00:29:44.560
but here's the requirement.

00:29:44.640 --> 00:29:49.020
I want the user to be able to
choose an effect and refine

00:29:49.020 --> 00:29:52.610
that effect in 10 seconds."

00:29:54.400 --> 00:31:19.400
[Transcript missing]

00:31:19.750 --> 00:31:22.120
But it would have also
given us complexity.

00:31:22.270 --> 00:31:23.900
Power and complexity,
that's not what we're after.

00:31:24.020 --> 00:31:27.680
What we want is simplicity and power.

00:31:27.870 --> 00:31:30.120
So why is this complicated?

00:31:30.120 --> 00:31:30.890
Well, it's three sliders.

00:31:30.900 --> 00:31:32.930
But not only that,
the user would be required to

00:31:33.040 --> 00:31:37.520
understand that you had to balance
these three sliders to always equal 100.

00:31:37.610 --> 00:31:39.580
So it's not like they could
just adjust one slider.

00:31:39.580 --> 00:31:42.740
They'd have to be constantly adjusting
all three to get the look that they want.

00:31:43.020 --> 00:31:43.440
And guess what?

00:31:43.530 --> 00:31:45.450
There's a ton-- you guys
are math geniuses-- there's

00:31:45.510 --> 00:31:47.120
a ton of options out there.

00:31:47.210 --> 00:31:50.680
And it would take forever for them to
see all of the different possibilities.

00:31:50.840 --> 00:31:56.390
So we said, OK,
how do we solve this problem?

00:31:56.960 --> 00:32:00.090
Well, with those three channels,
we sort of plotted the

00:32:00.230 --> 00:32:02.040
possibilities out on a graph.

00:32:02.040 --> 00:32:03.630
We said, "Okay, well,
here's a whole bunch

00:32:03.640 --> 00:32:04.440
of really nice looks.

00:32:04.440 --> 00:32:06.120
We'll plot them on a graph,
draw a line between them,

00:32:06.150 --> 00:32:10.340
almost like a timeline." And that
actually turns out a lot of really,

00:32:10.340 --> 00:32:11.610
really great options.

00:32:11.770 --> 00:32:15.640
Okay, so just sort of left and right,
you can see the different options.

00:32:15.810 --> 00:32:19.640
We take that, actually make that the UI.

00:32:19.820 --> 00:32:23.990
So, in fact, one swipe from left to right

00:32:24.520 --> 00:32:28.980
brings you through all of the black
and white mixing possibilities.

00:32:29.060 --> 00:32:29.620
So what did we do?

00:32:29.620 --> 00:32:32.380
We took three controls that you
had to understand the balance of,

00:32:32.780 --> 00:32:36.770
put them all into one control,
and allowed the user in just a few

00:32:36.870 --> 00:32:42.560
seconds to swipe back and forth and see
over a hundred different mixes of this.

00:32:42.650 --> 00:32:44.540
In fact,
we called this the happy accident UI.

00:32:44.540 --> 00:32:47.360
I always go through this and find one
that I never would have thought of,

00:32:47.360 --> 00:32:48.520
and I love the look of it.

00:32:48.620 --> 00:32:50.380
So this was taking a
complex idea and really,

00:32:50.380 --> 00:32:53.880
really simplifying it down
into one easy to use control.

00:32:53.990 --> 00:32:55.120
And this control worked elsewhere.

00:32:55.120 --> 00:32:57.890
So for example,
we have another one called Aura.

00:32:58.170 --> 00:32:59.850
Aura's a really neat effect.

00:32:59.970 --> 00:33:03.220
It allows you to sort of
highlight the strong colors in

00:33:03.220 --> 00:33:05.740
