00:36:56.140 --> 00:36:59.990
And let's talk about moving
from the iPad to the iPhone.

00:37:00.140 --> 00:37:03.990
You guys are eagle-eyed,
and you notice that every comp that

00:37:03.990 --> 00:37:05.680
we've shown you has been for the iPad.

00:37:05.990 --> 00:37:08.840
And indeed,
when we started with this project,

00:37:08.960 --> 00:37:12.440
we wanted it on the iPad with a big,
amazing screen.

00:37:12.620 --> 00:37:15.860
But then there was the point
where we said to ourselves,

00:37:15.960 --> 00:37:16.550
"Guess what?

00:37:16.640 --> 00:37:19.340
I take a lot of pictures with my iPhone.

00:37:19.340 --> 00:37:22.940
I think we need to have
this app on the iPhone."

00:37:23.370 --> 00:37:26.600
Now,
different apps should be thinking about

00:37:26.600 --> 00:37:29.640
this a little bit differently when
you go from one device to another.

00:37:29.790 --> 00:37:31.340
Not every app should do the same thing.

00:37:31.340 --> 00:37:34.900
So I want to talk to you about why
we made the decision that we made.

00:37:35.050 --> 00:37:38.350
We could have gone down
the path of saying,

00:37:38.390 --> 00:37:39.240
this is a great app.

00:37:39.490 --> 00:37:41.260
We want it on the iPhone,
but there's just too much stuff.

00:37:41.260 --> 00:37:42.460
Let's make it a simple app.

00:37:42.460 --> 00:37:44.240
Maybe we'll change the
UI to make it really,

00:37:44.240 --> 00:37:45.640
really, really simple.

00:37:45.800 --> 00:37:49.100
And, you know,
users will just have to go find an iPad

00:37:49.100 --> 00:37:50.660
if they want some of the cooler stuff.

00:37:50.660 --> 00:37:54.160
Like, nah, we won't do brushing or
any of those effects.

00:37:54.290 --> 00:37:56.560
You know,
the truth was is that iPhone is one of

00:37:56.560 --> 00:37:58.470
the most popular cameras on the planet.

00:37:58.630 --> 00:38:02.660
There's a lot of people who want to edit
their photos right on that same device.

00:38:02.790 --> 00:38:05.240
So the option of saying,
let's do a dumbed-down

00:38:05.320 --> 00:38:08.360
version for the iPhone,
it just wasn't realistic.

00:38:08.520 --> 00:38:11.150
So we had sort of a
challenge in front of us.

00:38:11.580 --> 00:38:14.950
How can we get all of this power,
all of this power,

00:38:15.080 --> 00:38:19.640
down on this tiny little screen
that can fit in your pocket?

00:38:20.210 --> 00:38:23.920
Well, if you've been listening to me,
you've been hearing me say, "Simplify,

00:38:23.920 --> 00:38:26.490
refine, repeat." You'll probably
hear it a few more times,

00:38:26.500 --> 00:38:28.020
just so you know.

00:38:28.100 --> 00:38:32.800
That process has many benefits,
and one of them is that when

00:38:32.800 --> 00:38:35.860
you move from one device and you
need to bring your application

00:38:35.860 --> 00:38:39.840
down to a different device,
you're going to have a much easier time

00:38:39.990 --> 00:38:42.100
if you've simplified those controls.

00:38:42.130 --> 00:38:45.490
If you have complex controls that
you can just barely fit on the iPad,

00:38:45.780 --> 00:38:49.040
you're going to have a problem
when you get to a smaller screen.

00:38:49.240 --> 00:38:52.240
Since we had gone through this process
of getting these controls simple,

00:38:52.260 --> 00:38:56.340
we had actually a surprisingly easy
time getting it to work on the iPhone,

00:38:56.380 --> 00:38:58.340
and it's really powerful.

00:38:58.380 --> 00:39:05.280
Every single feature that's
on the iPad is on the iPhone.

00:39:05.580 --> 00:39:06.750
So, how did we do it?

00:39:06.830 --> 00:39:09.530
Well, there were actually a couple areas
where we had to rethink things.

00:39:09.540 --> 00:39:11.620
So, for example,
you've seen the tool controls

00:39:11.690 --> 00:39:12.790
on the iPad at the bottom.

00:39:12.800 --> 00:39:13.760
You have this little tool bar.

00:39:13.760 --> 00:39:16.150
You can see there on the left,
those are your, you know,

00:39:16.160 --> 00:39:17.610
sort of tools that you can select.

00:39:17.610 --> 00:39:19.350
And then when you select one,
those tools sort of

00:39:19.520 --> 00:39:21.240
flip over on the right.

00:39:21.260 --> 00:39:23.480
Well, on the iPhone,
we don't have enough room for that,

00:39:23.480 --> 00:39:25.700
so we had to think of
something different.

00:39:25.700 --> 00:39:26.970
So there's those tools for the iPad.

00:39:27.080 --> 00:39:31.320
On the iPhone, what we did was we sort of
had a collapsible tool bar,

00:39:31.320 --> 00:39:32.160
you could say.

00:39:32.290 --> 00:39:35.200
So you can see the little
control on the left there,

00:39:35.320 --> 00:39:37.290
the little sort of tool box icon.

00:39:37.290 --> 00:39:39.980
You tap the tool box and
the controls come out.

00:39:39.990 --> 00:39:42.490
You select a control and they go away.

00:39:42.570 --> 00:39:46.440
So this was sort of a simple--we
realized that the answer wasn't

00:39:46.440 --> 00:39:47.880
particularly complicated.

00:39:47.990 --> 00:39:50.880
We just needed to make sure that
we were doing the right thing.

00:39:50.880 --> 00:39:54.030
Cramming a whole bunch of controls on the
iPhone would have been the wrong thing.

00:39:55.360 --> 00:39:59.200
Some of the other areas where we had a
little bit of a challenge was portrait.

00:39:59.400 --> 00:40:04.290
So on the iPad,
we have controls that work in

00:40:04.290 --> 00:40:05.540
both landscape and portrait.

00:40:05.640 --> 00:40:08.500
We knew that we needed to have
the same thing on the iPhone.

00:40:08.580 --> 00:40:10.100
On the iPad and portrait,
we still have a pretty

00:40:10.100 --> 00:40:10.990
good amount of space.

00:40:11.080 --> 00:40:13.150
So for example,
these really great exposure

00:40:13.150 --> 00:40:16.160
controls that Randy showed you,
they can fit on the iPad

00:40:16.430 --> 00:40:18.200
in portrait mode just fine.

00:40:18.290 --> 00:40:20.360
But on the iPhone,
there just wasn't room for them.

00:40:20.360 --> 00:40:23.400
We didn't want our users to have to,
you know, use tiny little fingers

00:40:23.400 --> 00:40:24.470
to get things to work.

00:40:24.690 --> 00:40:28.020
So the solution actually
wasn't very complicated.

00:40:28.120 --> 00:40:29.520
We split the controls up.

00:40:29.600 --> 00:40:31.860
So for example, there's three at the
bottom that you can see:

00:40:31.880 --> 00:40:33.490
highlights and shadows,
then the brightness,

00:40:33.500 --> 00:40:35.110
and then the contrast controls.

00:40:35.260 --> 00:40:38.450
You tap one of those,
an overlay comes up above it,

00:40:38.510 --> 00:40:40.520
and you get that very control.

00:40:40.820 --> 00:40:43.620
We did the same thing on the
color controls on the iPad.

00:40:43.620 --> 00:40:45.460
We have those great
sliders at the bottom.

00:40:45.510 --> 00:40:48.400
We just split them up onto the phone.

00:40:48.450 --> 00:40:52.290
The reason I want to show you guys
this stuff is because I don't want

00:40:52.420 --> 00:40:57.920
you to force your users to relearn
a UI when they go to a new device.

00:40:57.930 --> 00:41:01.850
If they go from an iPad to an iPhone,
don't ask them to relearn something.

00:41:02.020 --> 00:41:03.260
Use the same ideas.

00:41:03.370 --> 00:41:07.460
If the exact same control won't fit,
use something that they're going

00:41:07.460 --> 00:41:09.310
to know how to use right away.

00:41:09.740 --> 00:41:12.740
Now the final one that I want
to leave you with was brushes.

00:41:12.890 --> 00:41:15.440
So brushes,
we love the brushing feature and we

00:41:15.530 --> 00:41:18.140
