We change the angle of each brush.

00:47:42.900 --> 00:47:46.070
And then on the text,
you'll notice the text stays perfectly

00:47:46.330 --> 00:47:48.830
horizontal as the animation is happening.

00:47:48.900 --> 00:47:53.880
So we're just applying the opposite angle
to the text as we perform the animation.

00:47:53.900 --> 00:47:57.890
So when I tap on one of the brushes here,
the text stays together,

00:47:57.890 --> 00:47:59.900
the anchor points just move out.

00:47:59.900 --> 00:48:03.410
And then we actually
change the view ordering,

00:48:03.580 --> 00:48:07.600
or we change the clip to bounds
property on the toolbar and

00:48:07.620 --> 00:48:09.900
the ordering of that view.

00:48:09.900 --> 00:48:13.290
So when we tap on one of
these to start the animation,

00:48:13.290 --> 00:48:16.930
we bring it to the front and
then animate the center points

00:48:17.360 --> 00:48:18.900
together as it comes up.

00:48:18.900 --> 00:48:20.900
Like that.

00:48:20.900 --> 00:48:22.540
Now,
one of the things that you'll notice,

00:48:22.540 --> 00:48:24.660
when I tap on one of these brushes,
there's actually a

00:48:24.660 --> 00:48:25.890
subtlety to the animation.

00:48:25.900 --> 00:48:27.900
So I'm going to tap on the lighten brush.

00:48:27.900 --> 00:48:30.190
And as I do that,
the one I've tapped on is actually

00:48:30.190 --> 00:48:31.900
going to get a little bit bigger.

00:48:31.900 --> 00:48:34.900
It's going to pop as it's coming down.

00:48:34.900 --> 00:48:36.810
And the shadow is actually
moving accordingly.

00:48:36.900 --> 00:48:39.030
So as I touch that,
you'll notice that lighten brush

00:48:39.060 --> 00:48:41.900
actually extends outside the
boundary of the other layer there.

00:48:41.900 --> 00:48:45.040
So there's actually this extra
animation that's done when you

00:48:45.040 --> 00:48:48.880
touch on a brush to confirm that
that's the one that you touched on.

00:48:48.920 --> 00:48:54.900
But there's a complexity there in that
we've got two different animations going.

00:48:55.130 --> 00:48:58.710
And one animation is the one
that's changing with the angle.

00:48:58.920 --> 00:49:01.900
And the other one is that
pop effect that happens.

00:49:01.900 --> 00:49:03.970
We can go back to the slides.

00:49:04.490 --> 00:49:08.340
So there's actually a
really easy way to do that.

00:49:08.440 --> 00:49:10.640
You let Core Animation do
the work for you.

00:49:10.800 --> 00:49:14.150
So if we had this one view
with the animations on it,

00:49:14.150 --> 00:49:18.180
if I tried to put two different
sets of animations on that view with

00:49:18.180 --> 00:49:21.360
potentially different durations,
different offsets in time,

00:49:21.440 --> 00:49:23.890
that can be really complicated
to work that all out.

00:49:24.030 --> 00:49:27.510
The easy thing to do is to
simply insert another view.

00:49:27.920 --> 00:49:30.610
Now, this is a view just
for geometry purposes.

00:49:30.760 --> 00:49:33.450
There's no drawing that
actually takes place in this.

00:49:33.580 --> 00:49:36.430
But what it means is I can put
one set of animations on one view,

00:49:36.430 --> 00:49:38.700
the other set of animations
on the other view,

00:49:38.990 --> 00:49:42.280
completely different durations,
different offsets in time,

00:49:42.280 --> 00:49:43.260
and just let it run.

00:49:43.260 --> 00:49:45.410
And Core Animation will do
all the work of combining

00:49:45.410 --> 00:49:46.820
those things together for you.

00:49:46.890 --> 00:49:52.070
And you can extend this to as many views
as you want to do compound animations.

00:49:52.700 --> 00:49:56.780
So let's go back and to the demo machine.

00:49:56.820 --> 00:49:59.380
I want to show you one more thing here.

00:50:02.070 --> 00:50:06.000
So I'm going to go ahead
and switch over to effects.

00:50:06.120 --> 00:50:09.560
Now, so on the effects,
we've got something similar in here,

00:50:09.560 --> 00:50:13.670
where the effects are actually going
to come up to a different position than

00:50:13.670 --> 00:50:15.130
normally that you'd have in the UI.

00:50:15.140 --> 00:50:17.690
And we have the same red
outlines around the views.

00:50:17.780 --> 00:50:20.500
One of the nice things about
Core Animation is that it makes

00:50:20.500 --> 00:50:24.500
it really easy to take real
world objects and animate them.

00:50:24.620 --> 00:50:26.600
We've got these cards,
and we set them up.

00:50:26.810 --> 00:50:30.600
We just set the anchor point
at the point where that pin is.

00:50:30.680 --> 00:50:35.330
And then when we set an angle,
the card rotates right around the pin.

00:50:35.400 --> 00:50:39.480
So if you lay out the animations
such that they're similar to the real

00:50:39.480 --> 00:50:42.340
world object in the way it moves,
it makes it much easier to

00:50:42.340 --> 00:50:44.390
actually perform the animations.

00:50:44.660 --> 00:50:46.560
Now, we've got a couple of things here.

00:50:46.560 --> 00:50:50.890
If I select one of the cards,
like the first card, the artistic card,

00:50:50.960 --> 00:50:53.240
you notice all the other ones fall down.

00:50:53.290 --> 00:50:55.700
And this is a detail that you
don't normally see in the UI.

00:50:55.810 --> 00:50:59.200
The resting position of all those
cards is not all straight down.

00:50:59.200 --> 00:51:00.360
It's slightly off.

00:51:00.400 --> 00:51:01.900
They're offset from each other.

00:51:01.900 --> 00:51:05.040
And what that does is it gives
you that nice little kind of

00:51:05.040 --> 00:51:09.560
fanned effect at the tail ends of
the cards right around the pin.

00:51:09.810 --> 00:51:14.290
And you get a very realistic sort of
effect by just being careful about where

00:51:14.300 --> 00:51:17.640
the resting position is on the cards.

00:51:17.640 --> 00:51:21.570
Now, if I bring the cards up,
one other subtlety that I want

00:51:21.570 --> 00:51:26.190
to show you here is that when
I choose a particular card,

00:51:26.400 --> 00:51:30.200
when a card deck folds like this,
it folds in two parts.

00:51:30.200 --> 00:51:34.990
So when I touch on a card,
you've got the cards collapsing together

00:51:35.000 --> 00:51:37.760
and then the other cards moving apart.

00:51:37.850 --> 00:51:41.050
So we just had to split the
animation up into two pieces.

00:51:41.170 --> 00:51:44.110
One piece animates all the cards
that are going together in the stack,

00:51:44.110 --> 00:51:47.180
and the other one animates all the
ones that are going down below.

00:51:47.300 --> 00:51:50.080
And we just set the timings on
those so that they look like they're

00:51:50.080 --> 00:51:51.750
moving at about the same velocity.

00:51:51.860 --> 00:51:57.450
So it looks like the user is just sort
of fanning a card stack all at once.

00:51:58.290 --> 00:52:02.880
So that's some of the
animation that we did.

00:52:02.970 --> 00:52:06.880
One last thing that I want
to talk about is some stuff

00:52:06.950 --> 00:52:10.230
that we did for the UI layout.

00:52:10.450 --> 00:52:13.990
One of the things on the UI layout
is that we said that it's hard

00:52:13.990 --> 00:52:18.030
to know exactly how your user may
want to work with your application.

00:52:18.190 --> 00:52:21.370
Some users want to see
this grid on the side.

00:52:21.640 --> 00:52:22.480
Some users don't.

00:52:22.540 --> 00:52:24.880
They want to have the
image as large as possible.

00:52:24.940 --> 00:52:30.820
Some users may want to dedicate more
space to the grid and some less.

00:52:31.150 --> 00:52:36.210
So we allow you to grab the top of the
column and change the number of columns.

00:52:36.240 --> 00:52:39.390
This is really well received by users.

00:52:39.800 --> 00:52:42.760
But one of the things about making
a choice of putting something

00:52:42.760 --> 00:52:45.830
like the column on the left,
the grid column on the left,

00:52:45.830 --> 00:52:49.730
is that's sort of a bias towards
left-handed or right-handed people.

00:52:49.730 --> 00:52:52.880
And so some people are going to find it
very convenient and some people won't.

00:52:52.900 --> 00:52:55.250
And then there are just people
who like to have the grid

00:52:55.250 --> 00:52:56.340
on one side or the other.

00:52:56.530 --> 00:52:59.280
So we said, okay, fine,
we'll just make it so you can

00:52:59.280 --> 00:53:02.480
grab the column and move it
and swing it to the other side.

00:53:02.480 --> 00:53:06.880
And so the user has complete control
over how the interface lays out.

00:53:06.910 --> 00:53:09.400
Now, there are a couple of details here.

00:53:09.400 --> 00:53:11.010
When we swapped the user interface,
we found that the grid button was

00:53:11.010 --> 00:53:12.840
the only one that was in the grid.

00:53:13.090 --> 00:53:15.040
And so we wanted to make sure
that the grid button was the

00:53:15.040 --> 00:53:16.040
only one that was in the grid.

00:53:16.040 --> 00:53:17.950
And so we did that.

00:53:17.960 --> 00:53:19.960
And then we swapped the user interface.

00:53:19.960 --> 00:53:23.500
You'll notice that up in the top toolbar,
we have some controls.

00:53:23.500 --> 00:53:26.960
We have a grid button that we
want it to be next to the grid.

00:53:27.090 --> 00:53:30.750
So when you swap the
interface to the other side,

00:53:30.820 --> 00:53:35.740
those two groups flip around and
the grid button stays near the grid.

00:53:35.740 --> 00:53:37.690
And the same thing happens
down at the bottom.

00:53:37.690 --> 00:53:37.690
The tools stay

00:53:37.850 --> 00:53:41.460
Now, another detail here is if
I switch over to Portrait,

00:53:41.460 --> 00:53:43.100
one of the things you'll
notice here in Portrait,

00:53:43.100 --> 00:53:47.400
we set it up so that you can adjust
the size of the grid down here.

00:53:47.610 --> 00:53:50.040
And when you've got a grid
that you can see several rows,

00:53:50.040 --> 00:53:53.380
it makes sense for us to do
the scrolling up and down.

00:53:53.550 --> 00:53:55.870
But we wanted this to come
down and get to a single row.

00:53:56.140 --> 00:53:58.460
Well, when you get to a single row,
scrolling up and down

00:53:58.640 --> 00:54:01.290
doesn't work very well,
because you'd only be seeing

00:54:01.290 --> 00:54:03.520
a portion of two rows there.

00:54:03.840 --> 00:54:07.970
So as soon as we get to a single row,
we start to go left and right.

00:54:08.110 --> 00:54:12.820
But as soon as you pull this up--
oops-- as soon as we pull this up,

00:54:12.870 --> 00:54:14.600
then we go up and down.

00:54:14.710 --> 00:54:18.380
So it's making sure to take care of
all those little details of how the

00:54:18.380 --> 00:54:23.360
interface is going to be used by all
your different users is really important.

00:54:24.360 --> 00:54:31.520
So to wrap up,
Sam talked before about simplify, refine,

00:54:31.650 --> 00:54:32.040
repeat.

00:54:32.280 --> 00:54:34.920
And this is something that
we can't stress enough.

00:54:34.970 --> 00:54:37.460
You need to keep doing
this over and over,

00:54:37.510 --> 00:54:39.080
and then do it some more.

00:54:39.200 --> 00:54:42.810
Another important thing is to come
back to things with fresh eyes.

00:54:42.820 --> 00:54:43.820
We do that all the time.

00:54:43.820 --> 00:54:46.190
You get really focused
on a particular problem.

00:54:46.280 --> 00:54:48.830
You're doing this refinement.

00:54:48.960 --> 00:54:49.660
Put it aside.

00:54:49.870 --> 00:54:51.920
Work on another piece.

00:54:51.960 --> 00:54:52.820
Then work on another.

00:54:52.890 --> 00:54:55.000
But make sure to go
back to the first one,

00:54:55.060 --> 00:54:57.560
because you've learned things
along the way that you now want

00:54:57.650 --> 00:55:00.330
to apply back to that first thing.

00:55:00.610 --> 00:55:02.330
Another big one,
and this is a term that comes

00:55:02.370 --> 00:55:05.250
out of sort of the finance world,
is sunk cost.

00:55:05.330 --> 00:55:10.780
The amount of effort that you've put into
something in the past is not the reason

00:55:10.980 --> 00:55:12.790
for it to go into your application.

00:55:12.890 --> 00:55:15.930
The fact that you just spent
two weeks coding something,

00:55:16.000 --> 00:55:19.220
that's not the reason for that
to make it into the application.

00:55:19.340 --> 00:55:22.890
The reason for it to go into the
application is because it's the

00:55:22.890 --> 00:55:25.070
right thing for the application.

00:55:28.400 --> 00:55:31.010
It's a very easy trap to fall into.

00:55:31.300 --> 00:55:32.720
I'm sure we've all done it.

00:55:32.760 --> 00:55:35.380
You just spent two weeks
writing something really cool.

00:55:35.430 --> 00:55:38.080
The back of your head, you know,
maybe it's not exactly the right thing.

00:55:38.080 --> 00:55:39.720
There's a little bit
better idea someplace.

00:55:39.800 --> 00:55:42.370
But you just spent two weeks on this.

00:55:42.480 --> 00:55:44.860
Well, your competitors aren't
going to care about the two

00:55:44.860 --> 00:55:46.120
weeks that you spent on that.

00:55:46.180 --> 00:55:48.640
You shouldn't care about those two weeks.

00:55:48.770 --> 00:55:51.870
You should do what's right
for your application.

00:55:51.990 --> 00:55:56.100
And that leads to,
you should be throwing away good work.

00:55:56.160 --> 00:55:59.390
Because this means what's
left is great work.

00:55:59.490 --> 00:56:03.410
And great work is what
you want to strive for.

00:56:03.500 --> 00:56:09.820
And what that leads us to is,
in your application, good enough isn't.

00:56:10.190 --> 00:56:12.780
Great is what you should be shooting for.

00:56:12.840 --> 00:56:14.600
Thank you very much.